  As ASEAN accelerates its transition into the Intelligent Age, advancing responsible and competitive AI ecosystems has become a defining priority for regional growth. At The Powering the Intelligent Age Summit 2025, a private stakeholder dialogue convened policymakers, industry leaders, and global partners to explore how governance frameworks can serve as a strategic enabler for innovation.
  The session was opened by Akira Kadomoto (Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan), Dr. Jasmine Begum (Microsoft ASEAN), Fabian Bigar (Ministry of Digital Malaysia), and Tindaro Danze (Siemens Malaysia), who shared perspectives on the evolving role of governance in strengthening trust, accelerating adoption, and unlocking cross-border economic opportunities.
  The discussion underscored a critical and often overlooked point: strategic AI governance and clear codes of conduct are not barriers to innovation they are catalysts for competitive advantage. Nations that adopt transparent standards and strong accountability models consistently attract greater AI investment, foster stakeholder confidence, and position themselves as trusted players in the global digital economy.
  By defining sound governance principles for the development and deployment of AI across sectors, ASEAN can:
  Build high-trust digital markets
  Enable scalable public–private innovation
  Empower individuals, SMEs, and industries to adopt AI responsibly
  Drive inclusive and sustainable economic growth
  This session focused on translating these frameworks into practical action identifying pilot pathways, implementation models, and capability-building strategies to support AI systems that are safe, fair, interoperable, and globally competitive.
