  Moderating the “Role of Government in AI Adoption” panel at the AIX Summit organized by [Risin Ventures](https://qa.linkedin.com/company/risin-ventures?trk=public_post-text) was a timely reminder of how quickly the region is shaping the global AI narrative.
  We often talk about AI deployment and adoption as an entrepreneurial feat, but the truth is, governments across the GCC are taking bold, strategic steps. From Qatar’s partnership with Scale AI to deploy 50+ public sector use cases, to Abu Dhabi’s ambition to become the world’s first fully AI-native government by 2027, and the multi-billion-dollar AI infrastructure commitments announced by Qatar, the UAE, and Saudi Arabia earlier this year — the momentum is real.
  The discussion with Dr. [Fethi Filali, PhD](https://qa.linkedin.com/in/fethifilali?trk=public_post-text), [Dr.Sheily Panwar](https://qa.linkedin.com/in/dr-sheily-panwar-09182061?trk=public_post-text), [Klemensas Mecejus](https://ae.linkedin.com/in/klemensas-mecejus-589a9735?trk=public_post-text), and Perttu Korhonen revealed valuable insights on how governments have the strategies in place and are taking solid steps towards achieving them. We also addressed balancing regulation and innovation, investing in up-skilling and re-skilling, and creating ecosystems where startups, corporates, and academia all thrive.
  I also voiced a personal hope: that we soon see governments take their supportive role one step further, becoming active investors (G-VCs) in promising startups to accelerate impact at scale.
  A big thank you to my fellow panelists for their valuable insights and rich perspectives. And thank you to Risin Ventures for the invite to moderate this panel discussion.
  It’s clear that the role of government in AI is evolving — not just as a regulator or enabler, but as a co-creator of the future economy.
